00:20:37,529 --> 00:20:38,530
Yes, why not?

263
00:20:39,989 --> 00:20:42,784
Here, let me have it. I'll fix everything.

264
00:20:42,867 --> 00:20:43,701
Thanks.

265
00:21:14,732 --> 00:21:17,110
Paul said you weren't feeling very well.

266
00:21:18,778 --> 00:21:20,363
I'm fine, thank you.

267
00:21:25,452 --> 00:21:26,369
You look...

268
00:21:28,288 --> 00:21:29,247
worried.

269
00:21:31,249 --> 00:21:32,667
No, it's just...

270
00:21:35,462 --> 00:21:36,629
Just what?

271
00:21:40,467 --> 00:21:41,468
Hey.

272
00:21:44,596 --> 00:21:45,555
Tell me.

273
00:21:47,765 --> 00:21:50,185
I was making a cup of tea in the kitchen.

274
00:21:53,021 --> 00:21:55,398
I was alone in the flat,
and suddenly I heard...

275
00:21:56,149 --> 00:21:56,983
a noise.

276
00:21:57,066 --> 00:22:00,153
Then I came in here
and there was your husband.

277
00:22:00,236 --> 00:22:01,070
Who?

278
00:22:02,155 --> 00:22:04,574
- Your husband.
- What husband?

279
00:22:04,657 --> 00:22:06,493
Well, yours, my dear. Not mine.

280
00:22:06,576 --> 00:22:07,577
James?

281
00:22:08,995 --> 00:22:10,163
Your husband.

282
00:22:10,246 --> 00:22:11,664
I'm not married, Dad.

283
00:22:12,207 --> 00:22:13,082
I'm sorry?

284
00:22:15,251 --> 00:22:17,337
I got divorced more than five years ago.

285
00:22:17,420 --> 00:22:18,755
You remember.

286
00:22:20,965 --> 00:22:23,134
- Well, then, who's he?
- Well, who?

287
00:22:26,304 --> 00:22:29,224
Are you doing this on purpose?
Him who just left with the chicken.

288
00:22:29,307 --> 00:22:32,644
- The chicken?
- You handed over a chicken a minute ago.

289
00:22:32,727 --> 00:22:34,270
What are you on about?

290
00:22:34,354 --> 00:22:36,397
Did you not hand over a chicken
to someone?

291
00:22:36,481 --> 00:22:38,149
- The chicken!
- What chicken?

292
00:22:38,233 --> 00:22:40,151
What are you talking about, Dad?

293
00:22:52,080 --> 00:22:53,706
Well, he was here just now.

294
00:22:54,415 --> 00:22:57,043
I think you're mistaken.
There's no one here.

295
00:22:57,794 --> 00:22:59,963
- He's vanished.
- Who?

296
00:23:01,381 --> 00:23:02,966
The man with the chicken?

297
00:23:03,049 --> 00:23:04,259
Your husband!

298
00:23:05,301 --> 00:23:06,511
Why are you smiling?

299
00:23:06,594 --> 00:23:09,222
Nothing. I'm sorry. Sorry.

300
00:23:11,683 --> 00:23:14,269
All this nonsense is driving me crazy.

301
00:23:38,918 --> 00:23:40,461
What's the matter, Dad?

302
00:23:43,506 --> 00:23:45,466
There's something funny going on.

303
00:23:46,968 --> 00:23:49,429
Believe me,
there is something funny going on.

304
00:23:50,430 --> 00:23:51,889
Come, sit down. Come on.

305
00:23:59,897 --> 00:24:01,357
Now, don't worry.

306
00:24:02,483 --> 00:24:04,569
Everything will sort itself out.

307
00:24:06,654 --> 00:24:07,655
I don't know.

308
00:24:08,489 --> 00:24:09,407
Yes, it will.

309
00:24:11,117 --> 00:24:12,118
Don't worry.

310
00:24:14,454 --> 00:24:16,289
Have you taken your medication?

311
00:24:17,206 --> 00:24:19,083
What's that got to do with anything?

312
00:24:19,167 --> 00:24:20,710
Let's give you your medication.

313
00:24:20,793 --> 00:24:22,003
The evening dose.

314
00:24:22,587 --> 00:24:24,047
Then you'll feel better.

315
00:24:26,090 --> 00:24:28,051
It's been going on for some time.

316
00:24:29,260 --> 00:24:31,387
Strange things going on around us.

317
00:24:31,888 --> 00:24:32,930
Haven't you noticed?

318
00:24:36,100 --> 00:24:39,187
There was this man claiming
this was not my flat.

319
00:24:41,648 --> 00:24:44,067
A really unsympathetic-looking man.

320
00:24:44,150 --> 00:24:45,985
A bit like your husband, only worse.

321
00:24:48,154 --> 00:24:51,616
It's the best yet, don't you think?
In my flat. He told me.

322
00:24:57,914 --> 00:24:58,831
But...

323
00:25:03,753 --> 00:25:05,004
This is my flat.

324
00:25:05,755 --> 00:25:06,589
Isn't it?

325
00:25:07,256 --> 00:25:08,091
Anne?

326
00:25:10,968 --> 00:25:11,803
Isn't it?

327
00:25:12,845 --> 00:25:15,306
Tell me, Anne, this really is my flat.

328
00:25:17,225 --> 00:25:18,267
Isn't it?

329
00:25:29,779 --> 00:25:30,613
Thank you.

330
00:25:47,547 --> 00:25:48,381
Yeah.

331
00:25:49,507 --> 00:25:50,383
I know.

332
00:25:52,176 --> 00:25:53,010
I know.

333
00:25:53,636 --> 00:25:56,514
No. You can't imagine
how difficult it is sometimes.

334
00:25:56,597 --> 00:25:58,516
The other day,
he didn't even recognize me.

335
00:25:59,600 --> 00:26:00,435
I know.

336
00:26:01,769 --> 00:26:02,603
Yeah.

337
00:26:03,521 --> 00:26:04,355
Thank you.

338
00:26:05,773 --> 00:26:08,693
As long as he likes her,
that's the main thing, isn't it?

339
00:26:08,776 --> 00:26:11,362
And to know that he'll be happy.

340
00:26:12,864 --> 00:26:13,698
Yeah.

341
00:26:16,075 --> 00:26:18,619
No, that's a good idea. Yeah, absolutely.

342
00:26:18,703 --> 00:26:19,662
Hope so.

343
00:26:20,538 --> 00:26:22,248
She seemed nice on the phone.

344
00:26:26,335 --> 00:26:28,546
Well, I'll let you know how it goes.

345
00:26:29,338 --> 00:26:30,173
Yeah.

346
00:26:30,840 --> 00:26:31,674
Okay.

347
00:26:33,217 --> 00:26:34,218
Right, right.

348
00:26:35,052 --> 00:26:37,263
Okay. Speak soon. Lots of love. Bye.

349
00:26:55,364 --> 00:26:57,700
- Hello.
- Hello. I'm not too early, am I?

350
00:26:57,784 --> 00:27:00,119
No, no, not at all. Come in.

351
00:27:00,203 --> 00:27:01,370
- Come in.
- Thanks.

352
00:27:03,790 --> 00:27:04,916
So come in.

353
00:27:04,999 --> 00:27:06,709
- Thanks for coming around.
- That's okay.

354
00:27:08,211 --> 00:27:11,339
My father's just in his room.
Would you like something to drink?

355
00:27:11,422 --> 00:27:13,966
- No, thanks.
- Okay. Please make yourself comfortable.

356
00:27:14,634 --> 00:27:15,468
I...

357
00:27:16,260 --> 00:27:17,762
Yeah, so I was telling you,

358
00:27:17,845 --> 00:27:21,098
- my father is upset by the whole idea--
- That's okay.

359
00:27:21,182 --> 00:27:23,810
Yeah, so it can cause him to...

360
00:27:25,520 --> 00:27:27,313
I think he's quite annoyed with me.

361
00:27:28,022 --> 00:27:33,069
I'm just telling you this because
he is capable of reacting unexpectedly.

362
00:27:33,152 --> 00:27:35,154
Has he lived on his own up till now?

363
00:27:35,238 --> 00:27:38,616
Yes. He was in a flat not far from here.

364
00:27:38,699 --> 00:27:39,909
Which worked.

365
00:27:39,992 --> 00:27:42,453
And I was able to pop in on him
practically every day.

366
00:27:42,537 --> 00:27:44,413
But we've had to come
to another arrangement.

367
00:27:44,497 --> 00:27:47,041
- It wasn't viable anymore.
- I understand.

368
00:27:47,917 --> 00:27:51,254
He's had several carers,
one after another.

369
00:27:52,630 --> 00:27:54,924
He finds it difficult to get on with them.

370
00:27:55,007 --> 00:27:56,092
He has his ways.

371
00:27:58,427 --> 00:28:00,263
That's why I moved him in here with me.

372
00:28:00,346 --> 00:28:03,724
But I'm finding it quite difficult
to manage on my own.

373
00:28:03,808 --> 00:28:08,479
It's a bit much 'cause I have to work,
and that's why I need someone to help me.

374
00:28:09,689 --> 00:28:11,440
- Did I hear the bell?
- Dad. Yes.

375
00:28:11,524 --> 00:28:12,608
Ding-dong.

376
00:28:13,526 --> 00:28:16,153
- I'd like you to meet Laura.
- How do you do, sir?

377
00:28:16,237 --> 00:28:18,573
I explained to you
that Laura was going to come by today

378
00:28:18,656 --> 00:28:19,824
so that you two could meet.

379
00:28:19,907 --> 00:28:21,534
- Hello.
- Hello.

380
00:28:21,617 --> 00:28:23,744
- I say, you're gorgeous.
- Thank you.

381
00:28:24,245 --> 00:28:25,121
But I...

382
00:28:27,498 --> 00:28:28,916
Haven't we met before?

383
00:28:29,417 --> 00:28:30,585
No, I don't think so.

384
00:28:30,668 --> 00:28:34,046
Are you sure? I have a distinct impression
that I've seen you before.

385
00:28:34,130 --> 00:28:37,717
So Laura has come round to meet us

386
00:28:37,800 --> 00:28:39,427
so she can get an idea of how you live

387
00:28:39,510 --> 00:28:41,637
and to what extent
she might be able to help you.

388
00:28:41,721 --> 00:28:44,849
I know, dear. I know that.
You've already told me a hundred times.

389
00:28:45,558 --> 00:28:46,642
My daughter has...

390
00:28:47,560 --> 00:28:49,687
a tendency to repeat herself.

391
00:28:49,770 --> 00:28:51,772
But you know what it's like,
it's an age thing.

392
00:28:52,648 --> 00:28:54,275
Would you like a drink?

393
00:28:54,358 --> 00:28:55,776
You're very kind, but no, thanks.

394
00:28:55,860 --> 00:28:57,320
An aperitif? Are you sure?

395
00:28:57,403 --> 00:29:00,364
A little aperitif.
Time for an aperitif, no, no?

396
00:29:01,949 --> 00:29:03,409
Just a moment, I'll be back.

397
00:29:05,661 --> 00:29:06,913
He's going to find his watch.

398
00:29:08,748 --> 00:29:11,959
- I must say, he's charming.
- Yeah. Not always.

399
00:29:23,012 --> 00:29:26,015
Just as I thought, time for an aperitif!

400
00:29:26,933 --> 00:29:28,601
I have two watches.
I've always had two.

401
00:29:28,684 --> 00:29:31,062
One on my wrist and the other in my head.

402
00:29:31,145 --> 00:29:32,563
It's always been that way.

403
00:29:32,647 --> 00:29:36,025
- Now, what would you like, young lady?
- Dad.

404
00:29:36,108 --> 00:29:39,946
I'm allowed to offer our guest a drink,
am I not? What will it be?

405
00:29:42,448 --> 00:29:44,367
- What are you going to have?
- A small whiskey.

406
00:29:44,450 --> 00:29:45,618
I'll have the same.

407
00:29:46,410 --> 00:29:49,413
Splendid. Two small whiskies coming up.

408
00:29:50,790 --> 00:29:51,624
Anne, please.

409
00:29:53,626 --> 00:29:55,836
It's okay, Anne,
I'm not going to offer you a drink.

410
00:29:56,462 --> 00:29:58,547
She never touches alcohol. Not a drop.

411
00:29:58,631 --> 00:30:01,050
- It's true.
- Never. Not a drop, yeah.

412
00:30:02,301 --> 00:30:04,345
That's why she seems so...

413
00:30:04,428 --> 00:30:06,055
- So what?
- Sober.

414
00:30:06,138 --> 00:30:09,517
Her mother was the same.
The soberest woman I've ever met.

415
00:30:12,687 --> 00:30:13,646
Oh, dear.

416
00:30:14,355 --> 00:30:15,231
Silly.

417
00:30:15,940 --> 00:30:18,234
Whereas her little sister was
quite a different story.

418
00:30:18,317 --> 00:30:19,527
You have two daughters?

419
00:30:19,610 --> 00:30:21,696
Even though I hardly ever hear
from the other one.

420
00:30:21,779 --> 00:30:24,031
All the same, she was always my favorite.

421
00:30:24,115 --> 00:30:25,992
She was a painter. Look, there you are.

422
00:30:26,075 --> 00:30:28,327
<i>The Pirouette.</i> Beautiful, isn't it?

423
00:30:28,411 --> 00:30:29,495
Yes, it is.

424
00:30:29,578 --> 00:30:30,830
Yes.

425
00:30:32,248 --> 00:30:33,541
A dazzling girl.

426
00:30:34,125 --> 00:30:36,544
I don't understand
why she never gets in touch. Never.

427
00:30:38,587 --> 00:30:39,505
Your whiskey.

428
00:30:40,339 --> 00:30:41,674
- Thank you.
- Cheers.

429
00:30:50,558 --> 00:30:53,519
I'd give everything I own for a glass
of whiskey. Don't you agree?

430
00:30:53,602 --> 00:30:55,938
Well, I don't own all that much, so...

431
00:30:56,022 --> 00:30:58,190
Really? What do you do for a living?

432
00:31:01,027 --> 00:31:02,778
I look after other people.

433
00:31:02,862 --> 00:31:03,696
Other people?

434
00:31:04,572 --> 00:31:07,533
Yeah, my job is to help people
who need help.

435
00:31:09,035 --> 00:31:11,912
Sounds like those girls you're always
trying to dump off on me.

436
00:31:11,996 --> 00:31:13,914
Must be a difficult job though, isn't it?

437
00:31:13,998 --> 00:31:15,791
Spending all day with one of those...

438
00:31:15,875 --> 00:31:17,752
I couldn't stand it. Am I right?

439
00:31:19,670 --> 00:31:21,714
What about you?
What did you do for a living?

440
00:31:21,797 --> 00:31:23,382
Oh, I was a dancer.

441
00:31:23,466 --> 00:31:24,467
- Were you?
- Yes.

442
00:31:24,550 --> 00:31:25,718
- Dad.
- What?

443
00:31:26,719 --> 00:31:29,680
- You were an engineer.
- What do you know about it?

444
00:31:30,222 --> 00:31:32,266
Yes, tap dancing was my specialty.

445
00:31:32,349 --> 00:31:34,435
- Really?
- You seem surprised.

446
00:31:34,518 --> 00:31:36,020
- A little bit.
- Why?

447
00:31:36,103 --> 00:31:38,731
Don't you believe me,
or you find that difficult to imagine?

448
00:31:39,398 --> 00:31:42,943
Of course. It's just...
I've always loved tap dancing.

449
00:31:43,027 --> 00:31:46,197
You, really?
I'm still great at it. I'll show you.

450
00:31:50,993 --> 00:31:53,287
Jolly good. Why are you laughing?

451
00:31:54,246 --> 00:31:55,706
Sorry. Sorry.

452
00:31:55,790 --> 00:31:57,792
I know who she reminds me of.

453
00:31:57,875 --> 00:31:58,876
Who?

454
00:31:58,959 --> 00:32:00,669
It's Lucy. Lucy, when she was younger.

455
00:32:00,753 --> 00:32:02,588
- Lucy?
- Yeah, my other daughter.

456
00:32:02,671 --> 00:32:05,007
That's right.
There is a resemblance, don't you think?

457
00:32:05,091 --> 00:32:07,384
- Yeah, maybe.
- Yes.

458
00:32:08,677 --> 00:32:09,929
Yes.

459
00:32:10,012 --> 00:32:12,431
Her unbearable habit of laughing inanely.

460
00:32:17,394 --> 00:32:19,021
I had you there, didn't I?

461
00:32:24,735 --> 00:32:26,779
The situation is very simple.

462
00:32:27,363 --> 00:32:28,864
I have lived in this flat...

463
00:32:30,032 --> 00:32:31,200
for some time now.

464
00:32:31,909 --> 00:32:33,619
I'm extremely attached to it.

465
00:32:34,370 --> 00:32:38,749
I bought it more than 30 years ago.
Can you imagine? You weren't even born.

466
00:32:39,333 --> 00:32:41,001
Yes, it's a big flat.

467
00:32:41,085 --> 00:32:43,003
Very nice. It's very big.

468
00:32:43,879 --> 00:32:46,465
And I've been very happy here.

469
00:32:48,592 --> 00:32:52,805
Anyway,
my daughter is very interested in it.

470
00:32:52,888 --> 00:32:54,098
What are you talking about?

471
00:32:54,682 --> 00:32:58,811
You see, my daughter is of the opinion
that I cannot manage on my own.

472
00:32:58,894 --> 00:33:01,730
So she's moved in with me,
ostensibly to help me,

473
00:33:01,814 --> 00:33:06,777
with this man she met not long ago
just after her divorce.

474
00:33:06,861 --> 00:33:07,820
Yeah.

475
00:33:07,903 --> 00:33:11,198
Who has a very bad influence on her,
I have to tell you.

476
00:33:11,282 --> 00:33:13,200
What are you talking about, Dad?

477
00:33:13,284 --> 00:33:18,831
So now she would like to convince me
that I really cannot manage on my own.

478
00:33:18,914 --> 00:33:23,252
And the next stage will be
to send me away. I don't know where.

479
00:33:23,335 --> 00:33:27,381
It'll be a much more efficient way
of getting hold of my flat.

480
00:33:27,464 --> 00:33:30,843
But it's not going to happen that way.

481
00:33:33,596 --> 00:33:36,307
Sorry, dear. I may as well tell you now.

482
00:33:38,058 --> 00:33:40,436
I'm not leaving this flat any time soon.

483
00:33:41,312 --> 00:33:43,689
I'm going to outlive you.

484
00:33:44,899 --> 00:33:46,275
Both of you.

485
00:33:46,358 --> 00:33:47,693
I don't know about you...

486
00:33:48,694 --> 00:33:49,945
but my daughter, yes.

487
00:33:52,156 --> 00:33:54,200
In fact, I'm gonna make a point about it.

488
00:33:54,283 --> 00:33:57,870
I'm going to inherit from her.
Not the other way around.

489
00:33:57,953 --> 00:34:01,582
And the day of her funeral,
I shall give a little speech.

490
00:34:02,124 --> 00:34:05,544
To remind everyone how heartless
and manipulative she was.

491
00:34:05,628 --> 00:34:07,046
I'm so sorry about this.

492
00:34:07,129 --> 00:34:11,091
Why? She understands perfectly.
You're the one who doesn't.

493
00:34:11,175 --> 00:34:14,053
See, I've been trying
to convince her for months

494
00:34:14,136 --> 00:34:16,096
that I can manage very well on my own.

495
00:34:16,889 --> 00:34:19,975
But... she refuses to listen.

496
00:34:21,143 --> 00:34:24,939
I don't need any help from anyone.

497
00:34:26,315 --> 00:34:28,734
And I'm not going to leave my flat.

498
00:34:29,610 --> 00:34:31,946
All I want is for everyone to fuck off.

499
00:34:33,447 --> 00:34:34,698
Having said that...

500
00:34:36,242 --> 00:34:37,618
it's been a great pleasure.

501
00:34:38,202 --> 00:34:39,912
Au revoir. Toodle-oo.

502
00:34:43,540 --> 00:34:45,501
I'm really very sorry about this.

503
00:34:46,460 --> 00:34:48,587
You weren't kidding
when you said he had his ways.

504
00:34:48,671 --> 00:34:49,922
I'm really sorry.

505
00:34:51,590 --> 00:34:55,636
Don't be.
That sort of reaction's quite normal.

506
00:34:58,180 --> 00:34:59,306
It'll be all right.

507
00:35:00,224 --> 00:35:01,100
Do you think?

508
00:35:07,356 --> 00:35:08,190
Yeah.

509
00:37:01,845 --> 00:37:02,721
Well?

510
00:37:03,931 --> 00:37:04,765
What?

511
00:37:05,307 --> 00:37:06,266
Did it go well?

512
00:37:08,268 --> 00:37:09,103
Yeah.

513
00:37:09,978 --> 00:37:12,314
I think so. She said
she was gonna start tomorrow.

514
00:37:12,398 --> 00:37:14,149
- Here?
- Yeah.

515
00:37:14,233 --> 00:37:15,067
Good.

516
00:37:15,901 --> 00:37:17,986
Yeah. So we'll see
how the first day goes, and...

517
00:37:19,196 --> 00:37:23,117
I was worried it wasn't gonna work,
but in the end, it was fine.

518
00:37:23,200 --> 00:37:25,911
- He was charming.
- There you are, you see.

519
00:37:27,621 --> 00:37:28,747
Yeah.

520
00:37:28,831 --> 00:37:31,500
